{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7bcb193e-7e47-4bde-8542-1495aa7aff85","content":"Here's what you need:\n\n**Environment variables** (on your container):\n\n```yaml\nenv:\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump\n    value: \"1\"\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType\n    value: \"4\"                          # Full dump (1=Normal, 2=WithPrivateReadWrite, 3=Triage, 4=Full)\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName\n    value: \"/tmp/dumps/coredump.%p.%t\"  # %p=PID, %t=timestamp\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath\n    value: \"/opt/tools/createdump\"      # Required for NativeAOT — runtime doesn't bundle createdump\n```\n\n**Volume for dump storage** (add to pod spec):\n\n```yaml\nspec:\n  containers:\n    - name: my-app\n      # ... your existing container config ...\n      volumeMounts:\n        - name: crash-dumps\n          mountPath: /tmp/dumps\n  volumes:\n    - name: crash-dumps\n      emptyDir:\n        sizeLimit: 2Gi        # Size to at least your container's memory limit\n```\n\n**Key notes:**\n\n- `DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath` is critical for NativeAOT since the runtime is statically compiled and won't discover `createdump` automatically.\n- `MiniDumpType=4` gives full memory dumps — use `1` (Normal) if size is a concern.\n- `emptyDir` is ephemeral; swap to a **PVC** if you need dumps to survive pod restarts.\n- Set `sizeLimit` ≥ your container memory limit since full dumps can be large.\n- Ensure `createdump` has execute permissions and the app process can write to `/tmp/dumps`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9c39d2f8-45fa-4587-8683-513471bed88c","outputTokens":451,"requestId":"CB0B:5DA14:1F9EE5D:22E180A:6A05298E"},"id":"c653b74e-0944-4c60-8d27-1bb6af88dbd1","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:47:03.953Z","parentId":"5e509dc8-1708-4b3f-99f9-a87cd711c550"}
